		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="head" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						{ Omnis scientia est in artibus, philosophia, et
						professionibus; intim&egrave; intellectis. Et in his ipsis,
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Qui vnu[m] nouit peritissimu[m]
						artificem; omnes nouit. Nec proficit alius, sed aliud.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Erg&ograve; qua[e] a[e]dificant, in singulis pauca;						
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						in omnibus non multa; qua[e]
						onerant, in singulis long&egrave; plurima; in omnibus infinita.
						Artes; philosophia; professiones; soli fontes omnis
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						scientia[e], prudentia[e], et valoris.
						Hinc tot
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						) rivuli discursuum;
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						historiarum; omnis
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						necessaria[e], vtilis, aut potentis doctrina[e].
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Da mihi fixas scientia[e] stellas;
						non opinionis Cometas:
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						) Certas regulas;
						) no[n] incerta Orocanda. <!--JG: Orocarda?-->
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>All knowledge is in the arts, philosophy, and the professions; more intimately, it is in the understanding.
				And he who gets to know one most skilled craftsman in these very things, becomes familiar with all. Another person does not accomplish it, but another thing.
			Therefore, those arts accomplish things which are few in singular matters and not many in all matters; they oppress things which are many in singular matters for a long while, and infinite in all matters.
			Arts, philosophy, professions: the only sources of all knowledge, prudence, and valour. Hence all those rivulets of discourses, histories, all necessary and useful things, or powerful doctrine.
			Give me the fixed stars of knowledge; not the comets of opinion; certain rules, not uncertain [?]. <!--JG: Can't figure out the meaning of orocanda/orocarda--> <!-- CG: I'm not sure about the reading of the last two words either. Looks like he might have cancelled out something? And are we sure it's 'incerta'?-->
			</translation> 
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="EN">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Too good Newes, to be tru.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Gemina anchora priuatorum, Ars, et Virtus:
						Principum, Leges, et Arma.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>Art and Virtue, the twin-born anchors of private citizens. Laws and arms, [the twin-born anchors] of rulers.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						H&icirc;c omnis fundata prudentia.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>Here all the foundational prudence.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						Quantum fieri vir potest; et igneus furor; summa heroicoru[m]
						operum, et historiarum omnium.
						
						<!-- CG: Missing text added. -->
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>How great a man can become; and a fiery rage; the highest of heroical actions, and of all history.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
